# Architecture — Apps on Lakebase

This document answers the questions that came up in the May 20, 2026
architecture session. It is the single source of truth for **how apps share
Lakebase**, **how schema changes are promoted**, and **what is governed where**.

If you disagree with anything here, change this file first, not the apps.

---

## 1. Topology: one instance, many databases, one DB per app

```
                 Lakebase instance: hss-shared-lakebase
                 ┌──────────────────────────────────────┐
                 │  database: app_a_db   <- App A only  │
                 │  database: app_b_db   <- App B only  │
                 │  database: app_c_db   <- App C only  │
                 │  database: shared_ref <- read-only   │
                 │                        cross-app     │
                 └──────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Decisions**

| Question | Decision | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Project per app? | **No.** One shared instance per workspace. | Apps are used <5% of the time; an instance per app wastes idle compute and operational overhead. |
| Database per app? | **Yes.** One logical DB per app. | Schema isolation, per-app roles, no cross-app blast radius on migrations. |
| Shared tables across apps? | **Reference data only.** Put it in `shared_ref` DB, owned by the platform team, read-only to apps. | Juliana: "you can't have a shared table because the indexes are going to be different on each application." Indexes are per-DB so each app keeps its own. |
| Synced tables (UC → Lakebase) | **The consuming app owns the sync.** If two apps want the same UC table, each gets its own synced copy in its own DB. | Avoids index/permission collisions. Cost of duplicate sync is small vs. the operational pain of sharing. |

The instance name is a bundle variable (`var.lakebase_project`,
default `hss-shared-lakebase`). The database name is per-app
(`var.lakebase_database`, default `{{.app_name}}_db`).

